- eStat is an educational software for learning Statistics with dynamic graphs
- Easy user interface that the graphs can be drawn by mouse clicking.
- Include graphs and data processing for Elementary and Middle School level.
- Include topics on probability and statistics of High School and University level.

1. Data: Create / Save / Open

1.1 eStat Data: Create / Save / Open

    - eStat Data: Create
   Enter data on the sheet. Each row is an observation and each column is a variable.

      

      You can enter alphabetic character or number at each cell. Character data can be used to draw bar graph, pie chart, band graph.
   Only numeric data are allowed to draw dot graph, histogram, stem & leaf plot. However, alphabetic data are allowed for group variable of these graphs.

    - eStat Data: Save
   Enter file name on the above of sheet and click icon . File type is an Excel CSV(comma separated value) format.
   If you open this file of csv format, it looks like as follows.

      

     You can create this csv file using memo pad and open it with icon 'CSV Open'.

     Saved file is located on the download folder of your computer, for example C:/users/ .. /Downloads/).
   If you enter variable name and value label, you have to save file with 'Save json file' icon .

    - eStat Data: Open
   Data of Excel csv type can be opened by clicking icon .
   Select file in the dialog box of 'CSV Open' icon.
   Data of Excel csv type saved on other web server can be opened by clicking icon .
   Enter URL and file name on the dialog box.
   Date of json type can be opened by clicking .

1.2 Excel Data: Create / Save / Open at eStat

    - Excel Data: Create / Save / Open
   Enter data as the following example at the Excel.

      

     On Excel menu, select 'File' > 'Save with other name'. Select file type of csv(comma separated value) on the dialog box and then save.

      

     Saved file of csv type looks as follows.

      

     If you are not using English, eg Korean or Japanese, you might not see the header name or other characters of csv file at eStat. In this case, you have to save it using 'encoding' type of 'UTF-8'. Open this csv file by using the Memo Pad. On the menu, select 'File' > 'Save with other name'. Select 'Encoding' type 'UTF-8' on the dialog box, then save it.

      

     Now you can see the characters correctly when you open this csv file by using the icon .


2. Bar / Pie / Band / Line Graph

   - These graphs are suitable for categorical data such as sex, education level.
   - Continuous data such as weight and height need a categorization by grouping to draw these graphs.

   - Bar Graph : A graph that the frequency of a categorical variable is described as the heights of bar.
   There are various style of Bar Graph such as horizontal/vertical, Side-by-Side/Stacked/Ratio/Separated/Two-Sided.

   - Pie Chart : A graph that the frequency of a categorical variable is described as the slice size of pie.
  There is a doughnut style of Pie Chart.

   - Band Graph : A graph that the frequency of a categorical variable is described as the size of rectangle.

   - Line Graph : A graph that the frequency of a categorical variable is described as the line. The line graph can be also used for a summary data depending on time.

3. Dot / Histogram / Stem-Leaf / Box-Whisker / Scatter Plot

    - Dot Graph : Values of a variable are represented as dots on x coordinate. Dot Graph
   is useful to observe the shape of distribution, central tendency, dispersion. and outliers.
   If there are two groups, Dot Graph is used to compare means of two groups.

    - Box­Whisker Plot : 25 percentile(Q1) and 75 percentile of data are connected with a box,
   Median is described as a line on the box. Minimum and maximum are connected with the box as whisker.
   Box - Whisker Plot is useful to understand the shape of data roughly in case of large number of data.

    - Stem and Leaf Plot : Data are represented with stem and leaf. Stem is the all digit of data
   except the last digit and leaf is the last digit of data. This plot is not only a kind of histogram,
   but also provide information of the last digit. The range and shape of data are easily observed.
   If there are two groups, two sided Stem and Leaf Plot can be drawn.

    - Histogram : The range of a continuous data such as height can be divided into several intervals.
   The data can be summarized by counting frequencies of each interval and by drawing a bar graph, called Histogram,
   using the frequencies.In case of Histogram, there is no gap between bars.
   Histogram is useful to observe the shape of data.
   Histogram polygon is a line graph which connects peak of each bar.

   - Scatter Plot : Data of two continuous variables are representd as dots on the X-Y plane.
   Shape of the bi-variate variables, correlation and outliers can be observed using the Scatter Plot.

4. Probabilty Distributions

4.1 Binomial Distribution

    - Binomial Distribution
   Consider a statistical experiment which has only two possible outcomes, 'success' and 'failure' and the probability
   of 'success' is p, Repeat the statistical experiment n times independently and count the number of 'success'.
   The probability of 'number of success' is called the Binomial Distribution.

   P(X = x) = nCx px (1-p) n-x , x=0,1, ... , n

   Ex: When we toss a coin two times, the probability of number of Heads, 0, 1 and 2, is a Binomial Distribution.

   References:   Wikipedia   Wolfram   StatTrek  

[Example 4.1]
1) Simulate tossing a coin two times and observe the number of Head.
2) Draw the Binomial Distribution with n=10 and p=0.5.

(Solution)
1) (Binomial Distribution Experiment)
   - On the 'eStatU' menu, click 'Binomial Experiment'. Simulation result when n=2, p=0.5 will appear on the screen.
   - If you check 'show probability', actual and experimental probability will appear on the screen.

  

   - You can select other n and p, then click 'Execute' button to see its Binomial simulation.

2) (Binomial Distribution Funtion)
   - On the 'eStatU' menu, click 'Binomial Distribution'. Select n=10, p=0.5 and then click 'Execute' button.

  

   - Check 'show probablility' will show you the probability.
   - Check 'Normal approx' will show you N(np, npq) on the Binomial distribution.
   - Click 'Binomial Prob Table' will show you the Binomial probabilty table on the screen.

[Exercise 4.1.1]
1) Simulate tossing a coin 7 times.
2) Draw the Binomial Distribution when n=7 and p=0.5. Find its Distribution Table.

4.2 Poisson Distribution

    - Poisson Distribution
   The probability of the number of events occurring in a unit time interval is called the
   Poisson Distribution. If the average number of events occurring in a unit time interval is m,

   P(X=x) = e-m m x / x ! , x=0,1,2, ...

   Ex: Number of car accidents at an intersection is a Poisson Distribution

   References:   Wikipedia   Wolfram   StatTrek  

[Example 4.2] Draw Poisson Distribution with m = 1.0. Find its Poisson Distribution table.

(Solution)
   - On the 'eStatU' menu, click 'Poisson Distribution'. Select m = 1, then click 'Execute' button.

  

   - At the option menu, you can change m and watch various Poisson graphs.
   - Checking 'show probability' will print the probability of each bar.
   - Clicking 'Poisson Prob Table' will show Poisson probability table.

[Exercise 4.2.1] Draw Poisson Distribution with m = 0.5. Draw its Poisson Distribution Table.

4.3 Geometric Distribution

    - Geometric Distribution
   Consider a statistical experiment which has only two possible outcomes, 'success' and 'failure' and
   the probability of 'success' is p, When we repeat the statistical experiment until 'success' will appear,
   the probability of 'number of experiments' is called the Geometric Distribution.

   P(X = x) = (1-p)x-1 p, x=1,2,3, ...

   Ex: Number of tossing a coin experiment until Head appears.

   References:   Wikipedia   Wolfram   StatTrek  

[Example 4.3] Draw distribution of number of tossing a coin until Head appears.

(Solution)
   - On the 'eStatU' menu, click 'Geometric Distribution'. Select p=0.5 then click 'Execute' button.

  

   - At the option menu, you can change p and watch various Geometric Distribution.
   - Checking 'show probability' will print the probability of each bar.
   - Clicking 'Geometric Prob Table' will show Poisson probability table.

[Exercise 4.3.1] Draw Geometric Distribution with p = 0.3 and its Geometric Distribution table.

4.4 Hyper-Geometric Distribution

    - Hyper-Geometric Distribution
   Consider a population of size N which consists of D Success and N-D Failure. When we select
   a sample of size n, the probability of number of Success in the n sample is called a Hyper-Geometric Distribution.

   P(X=x) = DCx N-DCn-x / N C n

   Ex: A box consist of 100 items and 5 of them are defective. If we select 10 samles randomly for inspection from the box, the number of defectives in the sample is a Hyper-Geometric Distribution.

   References:   Wikipedia   Wolfram   StatTrek  

[Example 4.4] A box consists of 30 items and 5 of them are defectives. If we select 10 samples randomly, find the distribution of number of defectives.

(Solution)
   - On the 'eStatU' menu, click 'Hyper-Geometric Distribution'. Select N=30, D=5, n=10, then click Execute button.
  

   - At the option menu, you can change n and watch various Hyper-Geometric Distribution.
   - Checking 'show probability' will print the probability of each bar.
   - Clicking 'Hyper-Geometric Prob Table' will show probability table.

[Exercise 4.4.1] A box consists of 20 items and 3 of them are defectives. If we select 5 samples randomly, find the distribution of number of defectives.

4.5 Exponential Distribution

    - Exponential Distributiondescribes the arrival time of a randomly recurring independent event sequence.
   If λ is the mean number of arrival events in an unit time, its probability density function is:

   f(x) = λ e -λ x , x > 0

   References:   Wikipedia   Wolfram   r-tutor  

[Example 4.5] Draw an exponential distribution when λ = 1 and calculate P(1 < X < 4). Find 95 percentile.

(Solution)
   - On the 'eStatU' menu, click 'Exponential Distribution'. Select λ = 1, then click 'Execute' button.
   - To find 95 percentile of Exponential distribution, click 2nd radio button and enter 0.95 at the text box, then click 'Calculate' button.
  


[Exercise 4.5.1] Draw an Exponential Distribution when λ = 0.5 and find 95 percentile of the Exponential Distribution.

4.6 Normal Distribution

    - Normal Distribution describes data which are concentrated at the mean, symmetric with respective to the mean.
   If the mean is μ and the variance is σ2, the density function of Normal distribution is:

   f(x) = (1 / √(2π σ2) ) exp ( - (x - μ)2 / (2 σ2) ) , -∞ < x < ∞

   Ex: Height, Weight etc

   References:   Wikipedia   Wolfram   StatTrek   KhanAcademy   r-tutorial  

[Example 4.6] Draw a Normal Distribution with mean μ = 0, variance σ = 1. Find probability of P(-1 < X < 1) and find 95 percentile of the distribution.

(Solution)
   - On the 'eStatU' menu, click 'Normal Distribution'. Select μ = 0 and σ = 1.
   - Click the 1st radio button, and enter -1 and 1 at the text boxes. Then click 'Calculate' button.
   - To find 95 percentile of Normal Distribution, click the 2nd radio button and enter 0.95 at the text box, then click 'Calculate' button.
  


[Exercise 4.6.1] Draw a Normal Distribution with μ = 70, σ = 10. Find P(50 < X < 90) and 95 percentile.

4.7 t Distribution

    - t Distribution is a family of continuous probability distributions that arises when estimating the mean of a normally distributed population in situations where the sample size is small and population standard deviation is unknown. When a population is a Normal Distribution with mean μ, if we collect a sample of size n and its sample mean is m, sample standard deviation is s,

   the test statistic (m - μ) / (s / √n)

   follows a t Distribution with (n-1) degrees of freedom. t Distribution is used to estimate and to test the population mean μ.

   References:   Wikipedia   Wolfram   StatTrek   r-tutorial  

[Example 4.7] Draw a t Distribution with degree of freedom df = 10. Calculate P(-1 < X < 1) and find 95 percentile.

(Solution)
   - On the 'eStatU' menu, click 't Distribution'. Select df = 10.
   - Click the 1st radio button, and enter -1 and 1 at the text boxes. Then click 'Calculate' button.
   - To find 95 percentile of t Distribution, click the 2nd radio button and enter 0.95 at the text box, then click 'Calculate' button.
  

   - By checking 'show N(0,1)', a N(0,1) Distribution is drawn over the t Distribution to compare two distribution.

[Exercise 4.7.1] Draw a t Distribution with df = 5 and compare with N(0,1) Distribution. Calculate P(-1 < X < 1) and find 95 percentile.

4.8 χ2 Distribution

    - χ2 Distribution is a family of continuous probability distributions that arises when estimating the variance of a normally distributed population. When a population is a Normal Distribution with mean μ and variance σ2, if we collect a sample of size n and its sample standard deviation is s,

   the test statistic    (n-1) s2/σ2

   follows a χ2 Distribution with (n-1) degree of freedom. χ2 Distribution is used to estimate the population variance σ2.

   References:   Wikipedia   Wolfram   StatTrek   r-tutorial  

[Example 4.8] Draw a χ2 Distribution with degree of freedom 10. Calculate P(5 < X < 20) and find 95 percentile.

(Solution)
   - On the 'eStatU' menu, click 'ChiSquare Distribution'. Select df = 10.
   - Click the 1st radio button, and enter 5 and 10 at the text boxes. Then click 'Calculate' button.
   - To find 95 percentile of t Distribution, click the 2nd radio button and enter 0.95 at the text box, then click 'Calculate' button.
  


[Exercise 4.8.1] Draw a χ2 Distribution with degree of freedom df = 5. Calculate P(5 < X < 20) and find 95 percentile.

4.9 F Distribution

    - F Distribution is a family of continuous probability distributions that arises when testing variances of two Normal populations. When variances of two populations are σ12, σ22, if we collect n1, n2 samples from each population, and its sample variances are s12, s22

   the test statistic ( s12 / σ12 ) / ( s22 / σ22 )

   follows a F Distribution with degrees of freedom n1-1, n2-1.
   F Distribution is used to test two population variances σ12, σ22,

   References:   Wikipedia   Wolfram   StatTrek   r-tutorial  

[Example 4.9] Draw a F Distribution with numerator degree of freedom df1 = 5, and donominator degree of freedom df2 = 10. Calculate P(0.5 < X < 3) and find 95 percentile.

(Solution)
   - On the 'eStatU' menu, click 'F Distribution'. Select df1 = 5 and df2 = 10.
   - Click the 1st radio button, and enter 0.5 and 3 at the text boxes. Then click 'Calculate' button.
   - To find 95 percentile of F Distribution, click the 2nd radio button and enter 0.95 at the text box, then click 'Calculate' button.
  


[Exercise 4.9.1] Draw a F Distribution with df1 = 35, df2 = 5. Calculate P(0.5 < X < 3) and 95 percentile.


5. Population and Sample

    - Population and Sample compares the characteristics of population with the characteristics of sampling
   5%, 10%, and 20%. Comparisons can be repeated by collecting other samples with differenct populations.

    - Law of Large number shows a simulation that the probabiity of Head occurrence on tossing coin experiments
   converges to 0.5.

    - Central Limit Theorem shows a simulation that the sampling distribution of sample means with three different
   sample sizes. If the sample size is larger, distribution of sample means is closer to the population mean.

    - Confidence Interval shows a simulation that, if we collect samples many times and calculate confidence intervals,
   how many ot the confidence interval contains the population mean which explains the confidence level.

5.1 Population and Sample

[Example 5.1] Select a population of N(0,1), do experiment of sampling 5%, 10%, 20%. Compare statistics of population and sample.

(Solution)
   - On the 'eStatU' menu, click 'Population vs Sample'. Histogram of Normal population will appear on the screen.
   - Click one of 'Sampling 5%' 'Sampling 10%' 'Sampling 20%' button. Histogram of sample will appear on the screen.
   - By checking 'statistics/boxPlot', you can compare the population statistics and sample statistics.

  


[Exercise 5.1.1] Compare the statistics of Sampling 5%, Sampling 10%, Sampling 20%.

   - You can change the number of experiment n and click 'Execute' button..

5.3 Central Limit Theorem

6. Testing Hypothesis

    - Testing Hypothesis for Population Mean makes a decision to select one of two hypothesis about the population mean.
   Sampling distribution of sample means is used to test the hypothesis. (eStat, eStatU)
   If the population variance is known, Normal Distribution is used for testing. If not, t Distribution is used for testing.

    - Testing Hypothesis for Population Variance makes a decision to select one of two hypothesis about the population variance.
   Sampling distribution of sample variances, chi-square distribution, is used to test the hypothesis. (eStat, eStatU)

    - Testing Hypothesis for Population Proportion makes a decision to select one of two hypothesis about the population proportion.
   Sampling distribution of sample proportions, Normal distribution if n is large, is used to test the hypothesis. (eStatU)

    - Testing Hypothesis for Two Population Means makes a decision whether two population means are equal or not.
   Sampling distribution of the difference of two sample means, t distribution, is used to test the hypothesis. (eStat, eStatU)

    - Testing Hypothesis for Two Population Variances makes a decision whether two population variances are equal or not.
   Sampling distribution of the ratio of two sample variances, F distribution, is used to test the hypothesis. (eStat, eStatU)

    - Testing Hypothesis for Two Population Proportions makes a decision whether two population proportions are equal or not.
   Sampling distribution of the difference of sample proportions, Normal distribution if n is large, is used to test the hypothesis. (eStatU)

    - Analysis of Variance makes a decision whether two or more population means are equal or not.
   Sampling distribution of the ratio of between sum of squares and within sum of squares, F distribution, is used to test the hypothesis. (eStat, eStatU)

    - Independence Test makes a decision whether two discrete variables are independent or not.
   Observed cross table of two discre table compared with the expected cross table and chi-square distribution is used to test the hypothesis. (eStatU)

6.1 Testing Hypothesis for Population Mean

[Example 6.1] Consider 30 sample data of the Length of Otter (/WorldExample/31Cont_OtterLength.csv). Test the null hypothests whether the length of Otter is 70cm or the length is greater than 70cm. Use significance level of 5%.

(Solution)
   - Click 'Ex' icon, select '/WorldExample/31Cont_OtterLength.csv'.
   - On the data sheet, click variable name 'OtterLength'.
   - Selected variable number will appear on 'Var Select' text box.
   - Click 'Testing Hypothesis μ' A test result using μo = sample mean will appear on the screen.
   - Enter 70 to the text box of μo at the option screen. Select the alternative hypothesis H1: μ > μo    and significance level α = 5%.
   - Click 'Execute' button will show you the following result of testing hypothesis.
   - Test statistic is -0.871 and its p-value = 0.391 by using sampling distribution of t29 distribution. Therefore Ho cannot be rejected.

  

   - If you have a small number of data, you can use 'Testing Hypothesis: μ' menu on eStatU. You have to enter data directly in this module.

[Exercise 6.1.1] Using the same data of Otter length, test the null hypothests whether the length of Otter is 75cm or the length is less than 75cm. Use significance level of 1%.

6.2 Testing Hypothesis for Population Variance

[Example 6.2] Using the same data of Otter length in Example 6.1, test the null hypothests whether the variance of Otter length is 25 or not. Use significance level of 5%.

(Solution)
   - Click 'Ex' icon, select '/WorldExample/31Cont_OtterLength.csv'.
   - On the data sheet, click variable name 'OtterLength'.
   - Selected variable number will appear on 'Var Select' text box.
   - Click 'Testing Hypothesis σ2 ' A test result using the sample variance will appear on the screen.
   - Enter 25 to the text box of σo2 at the option screen. Select the alternative hypothesis H1: σ2 ≠ σo2 and significance level α = 5%.
   - Click 'Execute' button will show you the following result of testing hypothesis.
   - Test statistic is 21.606 and its p-value = 0.328 by using sampling distribution of χ229 distribution. Therefore Ho cannot be rejected.

  

   - If you have small number of data, you can use 'Testing Hypothesis: σ2' menu on eStatU. You have to enter data directly in this module.

[Exercise 6.2.1] Using the same data of Otter length, test the null hypothests whether the variance of Otter length is 30 or the variance is less than 30. Use significance level of 5%.

6.3 Testing Hypothesis for Population Proportion

[Example 6.3] A survey of 100 persons shows that 35 of them are in favor of the candidate A for the president. Test the hypothesis that the population proportion in favor of A is 40% or less than 40%. Use significance level of 5%.

(Solution)
   - On eStatU menu, Select 'Testing Hypothesis: P'.
   - Enter Po = 0.4. Select the alternative hypothesis H1: P < Po and significance level α = 5%.
   - Enter sample size n = 100, sample proportion p = 0.35, then click 'Execute' button. The following result of testing will appear on the screen.
   - Test statistic is -1.048 and its p-value = 0.147 by using sampling distribution of normal distribution. Therefore Ho cannot be rejected.

  


[Exercise 6.3.1] A survey of 100 persons shows that 45 of them are in favor of the candidate A for the president. Test the hypothesis that the population proportion in favor of A is 40% or greater than 40%. Use significance level of 5%.

   - Selected variable numbers will appear on 'Var Select' text box.
   - Click 'Testing Hypothesis μ1,μ2' A test result will appear on the screen.
   - Test statistic is -0.385 and its p-value = 0.707 by using sampling distribution of t13 distribution. Therefore Ho cannot be rejected.

  

   - If you have small number of data, you can use 'Testing Hypothesis: μ1,μ2' menu on eStatU. You have to enter data directly in this module.

   - Test statistic is -0.715 and its p-value = 0.474 by using sampling distribution of normal distribution. Therefore Ho cannot be rejected.

7. Correlation and Regression

    - Correlation Coefficient is a measure of relation between two variables which can have values betwween -1 and 1.
   If the correlation coefficient is close to 1 (or -1), two variables are closely related.
   If the correlation coefficient is close to 0, two variables are not related.

    - Regrssion Analysis is a mathematical model between two closely related variables.
   One variable (dependent variable) is predicted by other (independent) variable by using a regression line or other function.

7.1 Correlation Coefficient

[Example 7.1]
1) Simulate data of two variables which have a correlation coefficient 0.8.
2) Simulate data of two variables which have a correlation coefficient 0.3. Draw a regression line of the data.

(Solution)
1) (Correlation coefficient 0.8 simulation)
   - On eStatU menu, select 'Correlation Coefficient'.
   - Select the correlation coefficient 0.8, then click 'Execute' button. The following result will appear on the screen.
  

2) (Correlation coefficient 0.3 simulation)
   - Select the correlation coefficient 0.3, then click 'Execute' button. The following result will appear on the screen.
   - Check 'regression line' to watch the corresponding the regression line.

  


[Exercise 7.1.1] Simulate data of two variables which have a correlation coefficient 0. Draw a regression line.

7.2 Regression Simulation

[Example 7.2]
1) Create data on x, y plane and watch the change of the corresponding regression line.
2) Move a point to see the change of the regression line.

(Solution)
1) (Regression Simulation)
   - On eStatU menu, select 'Regression Experiment'.
   - Click the mouse on the x and y plane more than three times, then the corresponding regression line will appear on the screen as follows.
   - Whenever you click the mouse on the x and y plane, the corresponding regression line will appear.
  

2) (Moving a point)
   - Click a point by mouse and drag to other place on the x and y plane. You can watch the change of the regression line. Correlation coefficient is sensitive to the outlier.
   - If you check the 'Erase Point', you can erase any point.
